sql:
SELECT query_id, execution_time
FROM query_executions
WHERE cpu_usage > 13;

external_knowledge:
- "frequently invoked more than 10 times" refers to the count of query executions being greater than 10;
- "a fleeting moment" refers to an average execution time of more than 1 second;
- "production environment" refers to the database where `is_production = 1`.

- Performance issues are inferred from high execution times, frequent alerts, and high CPU usage;
- The average execution time and average threshold are calculated from historical data;
- More than one alert suggests recurring or significant issues.

- "Resource-intensive" refers to queries with higher than average execution time, CPU usage, trend execution time, and trend memory usage;
- "Generated alerts" means the queries have at least one alert associated with them;
- "Performance metrics" include execution time, CPU usage, and memory usage.

- "power-hungry beasts" refers to queries with CPU usage exceeding the threshold;
- "time-consuming titans" refers to queries with execution times exceeding the threshold;
- "marathon-like execution times" means the queries are sorted by execution time in descending order.

- 'developer' is a specific user role in the system;
- 'execution_time' is the time taken to execute a query, measured in seconds;
- The overall average execution time is the mean of all execution times in the `query_executions` table.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(query_id)
FROM queries
WHERE execution_time > (SELECT AVG(execution_time) FROM queries);

SELECT COUNT(query_id) 
FROM query_alerts 
WHERE alert_type = 'cpu_usage' AND is_resolved = 0;

external_knowledge:
- 'Read-only queries' refer to queries that do not modify the database but only read data;
- 'Average execution time' is the mean time it takes for a query to execute;
- 'Standard deviation of the query execution time' measures the variability or dispersion of the execution times around the average;
- 'Last updated at' is the timestamp indicating the last time the trend data was refreshed.

- 'Transactional' queries are those that are part of a transaction, which ensures that all operations within the transaction are completed successfully or none at all;
- 'Read-Only' queries do not modify the database, while 'Read-Write' queries can modify the database;
- The average execution time is a measure of how long it takes, on average, for a query to execute;
- A maximum execution time indicates the longest time taken by a query in a set of executions.

- "elephants in the room" refers to queries that are significantly resource-intensive and stand out among others;
- "excessive execution times" refers to queries that take longer than the average execution time;
- "high CPU usage" refers to queries that consume more than 50% of the CPU.

- "outgrown their expected performance limits" means the queries have execution times that exceed predefined thresholds;
- "alert thresholds" are defined as the maximum acceptable execution times for queries, beyond which an alert is triggered;
- "most recent execution times" refer to the latest recorded execution times for the queries.

sql:
SELECT query_id, database_id, avg_execution_time
FROM query_trends
WHERE avg_execution_time > 0.0002;

external_knowledge:
- "faster than a turtle but slower than a hare" refers to execution times greater than half the average execution time of all queries;
- "garden they were planted in" refers to the database ID;
- "flower blooming" refers to the query execution ID.

sql:
SELECT type_name
FROM query_types
WHERE is_read_only = 1;

external_knowledge:
- 'High-impact queries' refers to queries with an execution time greater than 0.001 seconds;
- 'Top 10 by execution time' means the queries are ranked by their execution time in descending order within their type;
- 'Most recent trend data' indicates the latest available trend data for each query.

- 'Resource-intensive' refers to queries with the highest average execution time;
- 'Heaviest anchors' is a metaphor for the most resource-intensive queries;
- 'Fleet of ships' is a metaphor for a collection of production databases.

sql:
SELECT *
FROM query_executions
WHERE execution_time = (SELECT MAX(execution_time) FROM query_executions);

external_knowledge:
- "The most recent run" refers to the latest execution of a query based on the timestamp;
- "Performance rank" is determined by the average execution time, with a lower average execution time indicating better performance;
- "Top 3" means the queries with the best (lowest) average execution times.
